ronment isn't ready), run apply then verify. So `on_probe_fail: skip` might actually mean the opposite of what I initially thought—skip when the probe fails, not when it succeeds. do when the probe fails? If the probe succeeds, we skip the apply step since the environment is already set up correctly. If it fails, we run apply to configure everything. So `on_probe_fail` likely controls what happens when the precondition check doesn't find the expected state.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4008,"cache_read_input_tokens":40760,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4008},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1087ea7-0578-456d-beca-38c538c0ca58","uuid":"5b28738b-3c35-40b6-9317-0ce431c85730","request_id":"req_011CcLuypaceFsGnVeg9RF1H"}
